{
  "text": "Additional support for these findings was found in an analysis of how experienced commanders make tactical decisions in realistic situations. Research was conducted to determine the decision requirements for command-level decision makers in the combat information center (CIC) of an Aegis cruiser. Analysis of 14 incidents from actual problems revealed 183 decisions. Of these, 103 concerned situation assessments. Decision makers arrived at 87% of their situation assessments through feature matching and the remaining 13% through story generation [CITATION_1] . Feature matching strategies involve comparisons of observed data to sets of distinctive features or cues held in memory and based on the decision maker's training and experiences. When a match occurs, as a result of conscious or more automatic processes, the meaning of the observed situation becomes evident along with the appropriate responses. Story generation, on the other hand, involves more active EBR processes in which decision makers attempt to build a coherent story that accommodates the observed data, thereby providing a plausible interpretation of the situation. Story generation typically occurs when the patterns of observed data are unfamiliar or insufficient to allow a match to features of known situations held in memory.",
